sical arts in England, in works by Van Dyck, Poussin and Handel. A second strand focuses on English responses to Tasso’s troubled life in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries, exemplified in Byron’s memorable impersonation of the poet’s voice in The Lament of Tasso.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aShakespeare 2018. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh  aAbraham Fraunce.  aEdmund Spenser.  aElizabethan England.  aGerusalemme liberata.  aJohn Dennis.  aRinaldo and Armida: A Tragedy.  aSamuel Daniel.  aTancredi and Erminia.  aTasso's art.  aTasso's poems.  aTorquato Tasso.  aamorous interlude.  aartistic afterlives.  adramatic opera.  aenchanted garden.  avisual arts.1 aLawrence, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610789340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526107893423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526107893/original  a978-3-11-128281-7  Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles